[DhtmlXQ_comment0]sg 20130204 2006QiXin Hong Zhi W Zhao GuoRong E34||2006?????????????||????????||||ECCO:E34 ???????????????||ECCO:E34 Angel's Pawn with Left Central Cannon Variation vs  Thundering Defense with Left Elephant Variation||||Jim: Found this game played rather recently in the 2006 QiXin Golf Cup. GM Hong Zhi took on GM Zhao GuoRong. I searched through my books and found a similar commented game by Sun ZhiWei and Liu HaiTing. The internet commentary was given by Master Zhao QingGe. I have combined their commentaries, with Z to present the comments by Zhao and SL to represent the comments by Sun and Liu.[/DhtmlXQ_comment0]
[DhtmlXQ_comment1]Jim: GM Hong Zhi is well know for his Angel's Pawn  opening.[/DhtmlXQ_comment1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment6]Z: Black gains a slight advantage in material with this variation while red gets to mobilize his troops faster. These are the pros and cons for each side.   ||SL: This game was played in round 12 in the 2006 QiXin Golf Cup (A League Tournament). ChongQing's GM Hong Zhi went up against HeiLongJiang's GM Zhao GuoRong, and both players began the game with the Angel's Pawn vs Thundering Defense. ||Black advances the pawn for an exchange and opts for an immediate material gain.||R9+1 is another huge variation which a different set of rules for attack and defense.[/DhtmlXQ_comment6]
[DhtmlXQ_comment13]SL:Red opts for material with this variation.[/DhtmlXQ_comment13]
[DhtmlXQ_comment16]Z: No matter what happens, black cannot allow red to play C1+3! If red were able to move C1+3, he would be prepared to play C8+5 on the next move to attack the central elephant and black's would be under heavy attack![/DhtmlXQ_comment16]
[DhtmlXQ_comment18]Z: Black's pawn would seemed to have made too many moves in the opening stages of the game, and has affected the development of the other chess pieces. However, R4+4 would give red the advantage.||Click on the variation to see Master Zhao's explanation, which are identical to Sun and Liu's explanation!  ||||SL: Black advances his pawn to keep his options open. If black tried R4+4 instead, red would still have the advantage.[/DhtmlXQ_comment18]
[DhtmlXQ_comment20]Z: Black traverses the cannon to protect his cross river pawn indirectly. If red does take the horse with H9+7, black would play C7+4 to threaten with a smothered cannon checkmate and thus capture the horse...BUT..[/DhtmlXQ_comment20]
[DhtmlXQ_comment21]Z: Red decides to sacrifice his horse anyway!!!||This sacrifice tactic is different from the usual tactics employed whereby one would get to launch a series of attacks after the sacrifice. Neither will it allow red to regain material a few moves later and have the advantage. The main idea behind this sacrifice is to control and limit the development of the black chess pieces. In exchange for this horse, red would now have spatial advantage and would try to exploit it in the moves to come. ||||SL: Red uses his horse to capture the pawn, preparing to sacrifice it for a gain in tempo. This is a very proactive and aggressive approach to the game.[/DhtmlXQ_comment21]
[DhtmlXQ_comment29]Zhao: GM Hong now further limits the movement of the black cannon as it cannot play C4=9 now. This would free his horse on the 7th file to start his attack.||SL: This is an improvment of C8-4 which was the move to make in the past.[/DhtmlXQ_comment29]
[DhtmlXQ_comment31]SL: Red's attack on black's horse would result in an unprotected black chariot. It would also trap the black chariot. This is a good move for red to increase his tempo and control of the game.[/DhtmlXQ_comment31]
[DhtmlXQ_comment32]Z: And after black is forced to move the horse, the side chariot is trapped and limited as it cannot move. The function of this side chariot is reduced to practically nothing.[/DhtmlXQ_comment32]
[DhtmlXQ_comment35]Z: And this was what I meant by red having the spatial advantage. Red gets to charge his central pawn forward for attack. Black, on the other hand, was forced to move his pawn and chariot too many times and that greatly reduced his tempo. ||Red's army looks very menacing now.[/DhtmlXQ_comment35]
[DhtmlXQ_comment37]Z: GOOD MOVE! Not only does red prevent his chariot from being attacked, he still does not give black any chance of developing his chariot(s).[/DhtmlXQ_comment37]
[DhtmlXQ_comment39]SL: As can be seen, the red central pawn has now crossed the river and one can feel that the momentum of the game is basically red's. The pawn can now control the riverbank and would allow red to conjure up many plans to gain back loss material.[/DhtmlXQ_comment39]
[DhtmlXQ_comment43]SL: Very delicate and polished move from red![/DhtmlXQ_comment43]
